    "reasoning": "Problem 1: The recurrence $f_{n+1}' = f_n f_{n+1}$ with $f_{n+1}(0)=1$ gives $f_{n+1}(x) = \\exp\\left(\\int_0^x f_n(t) dt\\right)$. Assuming the limit $g(x) = \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} f_n(x)$ exists and satisfies $g(x) = \\exp\\left(\\int_0^x g(t) dt\\right)$, let $G(x) = \\int_0^x g(t) dt$. Then $G'(x) = g(x) = e^{G(x)}$, with $G(0)=0$. Solving gives $G(x) = -\\ln(1-x)$, so $g(x) = \\frac{1}{1-x}$. Thus $g(0)=1$, and $m = g(0)+3 = 4$.\n\nProblem 2: $P_n$ consists of the origin and 4 points on each circle $x^2+y^2=2^k$ for $0 \\le k \\le n$. Squares in $P_n$ are of two types: (i) squares centered at the origin consisting of all 4 points on a single circle (one per $k$, giving $n+1$ squares), and (ii) squares with the origin as a vertex, formed by choosing a point $A \\in P_n$ with $x^2+y^2=2^k$ where $k \\le n-1$ (4 points per $k$, total $4n$ such squares). These two types are disjoint, so total squares = $(n+1) + 4n = 5n+1$.",
